Diagnosis
. Distinguished from known congeners by shapes of procursus and bulbal processes (
Figs 142–143, 146– 149
): distinctive weakly sclerotized obtuse process retrolaterally (arrow in 
Fig. 143
), ventral spine of procursus curved toward ventrally at half length, strong prolateral process, small prolateral ridge; ventral bulbal sclerite slen- der in lateral view (
Fig. 147
); tip of embolar sclerite with small cone-shaped processes (arrow in 
Fig. 148
). Females are difficult to distinguish externally from congeners; internal ventral arc strongly curved (
Figs 137, 140
, 
150
), lateral pouches of uterus externus long, with sclerotized lateral margins and visible in uncleared specimens (
Figs 136, 139
); median pouch of uterus externus large but membranous and not visible in uncleared specimens.

PALPS. As in 
Figs 124–126
; coxa with low retrolateral hump, trochanter barely protruding ventrally, femur with transversal dark line retrolaterally and distinct prolateral stridulatory pick; procursus (
Figs 142–143
) with distinct ventral ‘knee’, ventral spine long and curved toward ventrally at half length, strong pointed prolateral process, small prolateral ridge, distinctive weakly sclerotized obtuse process retrolaterally (arrow in 
Fig. 143
); genital bulb (
Figs 146–149
) with ventral sclerite slender in lateral view; tip of embolar sclerite with small cone-shaped processes (arrow in 
Fig. 148
); with distinct dorsal membranous process (
Fig. 147
).
